# cv-bullets config

Copy this file to `~/.claude/skills/cv-bullets/config.md` and fill in your own
values. The skill reads it at the start of every run (Phase 0). It is git-ignored
in this repo, so your personal data never gets committed.

## Parameters

### cv_path

Absolute path to the folder that holds your CV data files. The skill expects
`content/cv.pl.ts` (Polish) and `content/cv.en.ts` (English) under this path,
and writes inventory files to `content/data-inventories/` there.

```
cv_path: ~/dev/cv/
```

Used in:
- **Phase 0** — to locate and read the existing CV for the "new entry vs refinement"
  check and for style mirroring.
- **Phase 1 / Phase 7** — to read and write `cv.pl.ts` / `cv.en.ts`.
- **Phase 4.5** — to save the inventory markdown under `<cv_path>/content/data-inventories/`.

### git_author_pattern

Substring passed to `git log --author` so the skill can isolate *your* commits in
a repo. It can be a GitHub nick, a fragment of your email, or your name — whatever
reliably matches your commits. Matching is case-insensitive and checks both the
author name and email.

If you commit from several accounts (e.g. work + personal email, or a renamed
GitHub handle), list a few patterns separated by commas — the skill will try each.

```
git_author_pattern: your-github-nick, you@example.com, Your Name
```

Used in:
- **Phase 2** — as the `--author` value for `scripts/analyze_git.py`.
- **Phase 0 / Step 1.1** — as the `--author` value for `scripts/scan_siblings.py`
  when detecting which sibling repos you contributed to.
